2 TITL Elizabeth Ingraham Lenentine
1 _OID 063398fd-d7f5-4155-8071-60064ce38645
1 _META <metadataxml><content><line>&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: small;"&gt;Elizabeth Ingraham Lenentine is my great grand mother . Her youngest daughter, Gertrude, is my grand mother. In her lifetime elizabeth married twice, gave birth to eight chi
2 CONC ldren, starting when she was 26 and not finishing ubntil she was 50! &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</line><line>&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: small;"&gt;At 43 she gave birth to Gertude, a beautiful child, and possibly a little spoiled as by this tim
2 CONC e her mother had a lot of older children. as older siblings will tend to do, they undoubtedly pampered and spolied this child gertude&amp;nbsp; who became&amp;nbsp; accustomed to getting her own way .&lt;br&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</line><line>&l
2 CONC t;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: small;"&gt;At 50 she gave birth to Norman who may have been equally doted upon and by this time Gertrude may have had her nose out of joint . She had had seven years of being the youngest. Moses, twelve years Eliza
2 CONC beth's senior, at 62 may have found the rigors of parent hood more than a little exhausting.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</line><line>&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: small;"&gt;&lt;br&gt;Norman may have been challenged , perhaps physicall
2 CONC y but presumably mentally. The stigma attached to a mentally challenged child at that time was not the broad view we are developing today. for a time Norman worked in his older brother's store, located today on the tourist attraction, kings' Landin
2 CONC g. however norman is recorded at the age of 28 as being a resident of Lancaster parish&amp;nbsp; at Lancaster Heights, Fairville. Fairville at that time was known as the location of an asylum for the insane. Norman was 28 at the time. i am still wo
2 CONC rkimng on his death, presumably early.&lt;br&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</line></content></metadataxml>
