2 TITL General Notes for J. Reuben Bridges
1 _OID 0df8d862-ae27-4bbf-8292-52d5f290178a
1 _META <metadataxml><content><line>&lt;p&gt;Reuben Bridges had red hair. He was among many young men who worked in the mines in Leadville, Colorado, and Reuben lost an eye while working in the mines. Reuben returned to farm in Mars Hill. He and Hannah ar
2 CONC e buried in Pierce Cemetery on the Fort Road in Mars Hill.&lt;/p&gt;</line><line>&lt;p&gt;Extract from &lt;em&gt;Mars Hill&lt;/em&gt; by Gladys Sylvester Tweedie, Northern Printers, Presque Isle, Maine, 1952&amp;nbsp;-&lt;/p&gt;</line><line>&lt;p&g
2 CONC t;Page 15 - &quot;Reuben Bridges and his son, Holland, lived on the West Ridge Road. Howard, son of Holland, is a prosperous farmer there at the present time. He lives on the place formerly owned by Alden Sylvester.&quot; Page 19- &quot;Reuben Brid
2 CONC ges was helping Colonel Rackliff build a barn, and one afternoon he was anxious to leave, but hated to tell the Colonel. He wanted to get married that afternoon. At noon one man said he had to go home, another one had an excuse also, so Reuben wa
2 CONC s able to carry out his plan. Reuben was the second man to drive a team up the Fort Road. George West drove one up the day before he did.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;</line><line>&lt;p&gt;Extract from &lt;em&gt;A History of Mars Hill&lt;/em&gt; by Seth L. Sno
2 CONC w -&lt;/p&gt;</line><line>&lt;p&gt;Chapter II - &quot;Mr. and Mrs. Gilman being young people with a party of their friends from the Presque Isle road went, they said to husk corn. The party consisted of the following couples; John Ruggles and Mrs
2 CONC . Ruggles, Reuben Bridges [sister] who is now Mrs Cyrus Shaw. This party started at Mr. Bridges&apos; and went up to where S. P. Winslow now lives a distance of about two miles, Jim McDonogh lived there then, there they took a lumber road through t
2 CONC he woods, easterly for about a mile to the stream, crossing it about opposite where G. F. Blackden now lives, then up over the hill to Gillman&apos;s. They had to ford the stream and the fellows had to carry the girls across. Now Fred Snow was stou
2 CONC t and strong and Miss Bridges being light they got over easily. Not so for Bridges and Banks with the girls they were escorting, for Mariah Bell and Mary Bridges were large and Tom and Rube had almost more than they bargained for to get them across
2 CONC .&quot;&lt;/p&gt;</line><line>&lt;p&gt;Chapter XII - &quot;In 1876, Reuben Bridges and Wayman Shaw went to Colorado. A good many men from the town went West most of whom returned to Mars Hill after spending a few years there. Mr. Bridges was in Col
2 CONC orado nearly seven years. When he first went he worked for awhile in Michigan, then went to Nesco County, Kansas, and from there he and Mr. Shaw went the overland route to Leadville. They went by mule team up the Arkansas river, being 19 days on th
2 CONC e trail. They met many men returning with all kinds of stones. Once they were told that if they had any money they would be killed and robbed, and if they did not have any money they would starve to death and that the only thing they could get to d
2 CONC o was digging graves at $2.50 a piece, altogether a rather gloomy prospect. A good many men from Mars Hill made trips West in search for wealth; many returned after a few years to the old home and farm; a few however, have made a home in some weste
2 CONC rn state.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;</line></content></metadataxml>
