2 TITL Burial Location of Zimri Fuller
1 _OID 2a75702e-5cdf-4f81-8dcc-6080c2aa3261
1 _META <metadataxml><content><line>Ray and Hazel Boynton Clifford knew the location of Zimri&amp;#39;s grave, but it was lost to the past when they died. Zimri was her grandfather. Hazel&amp;#39;s mother was Alice Fuller, Zimri&amp;#39;s daughter. There&a
2 CONC mp;#39;s no doubt that Alice visited her father&amp;#39;s grave from time to time with her children. As it was explained to me by Harold Whitney, when Zimri died he was a pauper and no one in the family had the funds to pay for a lot in any cemeter
2 CONC y, so he was buried on town property behind the old Town Hall in Freedom in a row of unmarked graves. Zimri&amp;#39;s grave was marked by a white rose bush that had been planted to mark the location. The problem is that Freedom has had a couple o
2 CONC f old town halls. Back then, towns buried their paupers on town property to save money, and no stone was purchased to mark the graves. Whoever owns the property today has no idea that these graves are there. Frank and Alice Boynton lived and raise
2 CONC d their family in Freedom. Dr. Small had his home and office in the middle of town and Frank and Alice Boynton lived on his farm where they worked and took care of it. Frank used to drive the horse and buggy for Doctor Small on his rounds to see hi
2 CONC s patients. Aunt Hazel died in 1962 and Uncle Ray probably never went back to Zimri&amp;#39;s grave after that, so time has erased everything. Harold Whitney was born in 1915 and he lived with Frank and Alice in Freedom as a young child while his m
2 CONC other lived away from home working as a domestic doing house work in Portland. Aunt Florence Boynton Harvey, in conversation with me and her grandaughter Betty Richards made the statement &amp;quot;Hazel Clifford had a white rose bush on her lawn w
2 CONC hich she said was started from a slip of the rose bush from Zimri Fuller&amp;#39;s grave.&amp;quot; Ray and Hazel Clifford lived in Weeks Mills. Ella Spencer made the following statement, &amp;quot;Uncle George always told me that his father was bu
2 CONC ried up in back of the old Town House. He planted a rose bush on the grave the last time he visited it.&amp;quot;</line></content></metadataxml>
