2 TITL Biography of Samuel Getchell
1 _OID 4470b493-d2f5-47d3-816a-baab296b91fd
1 DATE 1636
1 PLAC Massachussetts
1 _DSCR from
2 CONT http://www.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~nbststep/stst8e.htm
1 _META <metadataxml><content><line>&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; Samuel Getchell is said to have come with his brother, John, from England to Salem in the Massachusetts Bay Colony in 1636. He and John were taxed at Marblehead on 1 Ja
2 CONC n 1637/8 and were granted a 6 acre lot on the Neck at Marblehead which was laid out on 14 Nov 1638 [1].&amp;nbsp; He was called &amp;ldquo;Samuel Gatchell of Marblehead&amp;rdquo; in a legal action brought by William Vincen at Salem 25 Jan 1641/2 [
2 CONC 2, V4, P59] and sold his real estate, presumably at Marblehead, in 1644 [-].&amp;nbsp; Samuel is mentioned as a debtor in the probate of the estate of Geo. Pollard of Marblehead 31 Dec 1646 [2].&amp;nbsp; Samuel settled in Hampton, New Hampshire, b
2 CONC uying from William Hunton a 5 acre house lot and a 2.5 acre upland lot.&amp;nbsp; As the proprietor of a house lot, he was granted a 1/147 interest in the Hampton &amp;ldquo;cow common&amp;rdquo; on 23 Feb 1646/7 [31]. He later sold his &amp;ldquo;
2 CONC late dwelling house&amp;rdquo; and land to William Godfrey of Hampton, 17 May 1648 [2, V1], and settled at Salisbury, Mass., in whose records he is called a &amp;ldquo;planter&amp;rdquo;, the same year (ELG says 1647).&amp;nbsp; The Salisbury recor
2 CONC ds also indicate that he was a commoner, that he was taxed in 1650 and 1652, and that he received land in 1654 [3].&amp;nbsp; He traded 3 acres of marsh to Edward Cottle for 30 shillings worth of boards &amp;ldquo;after the new mill begins to saw&a
2 CONC mp;rdquo; 29 Sep 1658 [2, V2, P114].&amp;nbsp; Samuel and his wife,&amp;nbsp; Dorcas, transferred 9 acres of land in Salisbury to their daughter, Susannah, and her husband, Joseph Norton, 11 Apr 1665 [2].&amp;nbsp; This document indicates that bot
2 CONC h Samuel and Dorcas were illiterate, Samuel signing with a mark resembling an &amp;ldquo;A&amp;rdquo; and Dorcas with a mark resembling a &amp;ldquo;2&amp;rdquo;.&amp;nbsp; In 1678, Samuel sued Saml. Fowler and, in 1680, he and Dorcas were associat
2 CONC ed with Mary Osgood and Philip Rowell and his wife, Sarah, in action against John Ring and Martha Lampson [4].&amp;nbsp; It is said [4] that Samuel&amp;rsquo;s wills of 2 Apr 1684 and 6 Oct 1697 named his wife and children.&amp;nbsp; Presumably, th
2 CONC is means that all are accounted for in the two wills combined as Dorcas is presumed to be dead long before 1697.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;[1]&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &lt;em&gt;The History of Salem, Massachusetts&lt;/em&
2 CONC gt;, Volume II, Sidney Perley, self-published, Salem,&amp;nbsp; Mass., 1926 &lt;br&gt; [2]&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; Old Norfolk County (Massachusetts) records as abstracted in the &lt;em&gt;Essex Antiquarian&lt;/em&gt;&amp;
2 CONC nbsp; (&amp;ldquo;V_&amp;rdquo; indicates &lt;em&gt;Essex Antiquarian&lt;/em&gt; volume number) &lt;br&gt; [3]&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &lt;em&gt;Old Families of Salisbury and Amesbury&lt;/em&gt; (Massachusetts),&amp;nbsp
2 CONC ; David Hoyt &lt;br&gt; [4]&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &lt;em&gt;Genealogical Dictionary of Maine and New Hampshire&lt;/em&gt;, Noyes, Libby, and Davis&amp;nbsp; &lt;/p&gt;</line></content></metadataxml>
