2 TITL General Notes for John Hollon Bridges
1 _OID 664056a9-acf7-4335-b9f8-f580943983a2
1 _META <metadataxml><content><line>&lt;p&gt;Hollon Bridges was born in Sunbury County, N.B. He was about eighteen years old when his family moved to Lakeville, Carleton County, N.B., in 1832. Hollon's address at the time of his marriage in 1837 was Jackso
2 CONC ntown, N.B. Sarah had been born in N.B. and moved to Bridgewater with her parents in 1829. Hollon and Sarah first settled in Bridgewater and moved in 1840, as did Sarah's parents, to Deerfield Academy (now Westfield). Here Hollon and James Thorncro
2 CONC ft operated a tavern on the Military Road. In 1848 Hollon and family moved to Mars Hill, Maine. Several years prior to this move, Hollon had been clearing land in Mars Hill with his brother-in-law, John Ruggles. Hollon Bridges built the first fram
2 CONC e house in Mars Hill. From his father's will, Hollon was to receive 25&amp;pound; or the equivalent in stock over two years. Thomas and William Bridges were to pay 10&amp;pound; each and Robert Bridges 5&amp;pound;.&lt;/p&gt;</line><line>&lt;p&gt;E
2 CONC xtract from &lt;em&gt;A History of Mars Hill&lt;/em&gt; by Seth L. Snow -&lt;/p&gt;</line><line>&lt;p&gt;Chapter II - "In 1840 Holland Bridges moved to Westfield and was there in company with Mr. Thorn until 1848. Althea D. Bridges, now Mrs. Cyru
2 CONC s Shaw was born in Westfield. When Mrs. Shaw was seven years old or in 1848, Mr. Bridges moved to Mars Hill. He had built a house on the east side of the road on the hill south of where Frank Jones lives. This was the first frame house in the town.
2 CONC ..Mr. Bridges kept some sheep and Mrs. Shaw remembers how they used to card the wool, spin the rolls and weave cloth for the family. She says "When we came to Mars Hill it was all woods. There were no schools to go to. The only light we had at nigh
2 CONC t was a tallow-dip candle. There were three settlers in the town when we came. The first cook stove brought into the town was brought by my Uncle John Ruggles, and we all turned out to see it. It was a 'wonder'."&amp;hellip;Mrs. Shaw has lived in t
2 CONC he town longer than any other woman&amp;hellip;Mr. Bridges cut the trees where the A.C.I. now stands, in about 1852. Reuben Bridges helped his father clear the&amp;nbsp;fields and Mrs. Shaw in the Spring of 1853 planted corn among the stumps wher
2 CONC e the Institute today is."&lt;/p&gt;</line><line>&lt;p&gt;Extract from &lt;em&gt;Mars Hill&lt;/em&gt; by Gladys Sylvester Tweedie -&lt;/p&gt;</line><line>&lt;p&gt;Page 19 - "The Blanchards were the first people to raise wheat in the eastern part o
2 CONC f the town. In 1861, Mrs. Lucy Hawksley&amp;hellip;and Mrs. (Holland) Bridges walked to Gilbert Blanchard's farm and cut a bundle of wheat straw to bind into hats."&lt;/p&gt;</line><line>&lt;p&gt;Page 39 - "What is known as the Military Road starte
2 CONC d at a point near Bridgewater Corner and went west to Mars Hill, through the dense wilderness to Presque Isle. This road was made for the soldiers of the Aroostook War. The road went by the Tavern, kept by Holland Bridges and Mr. Thorne, in Westfie
2 CONC ld (Ralph Lamont farm)&amp;hellip;The Fort Road, known as Ellis Tote Road, went from Bridges' place across the hill, through the woods and connected with the present Fort Road at the bridge in Mars Hill village. Reuben Bridges helped his father, Ho
2 CONC lland, grub this road out in 1856."&lt;/p&gt;</line></content></metadataxml>
