2 TITL A History of the Town of Unity, Maine
1 _OID 9120657c-2bae-4115-81e9-a3d07f4c9730
1 _META <metadataxml><content><line>&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: small;"&gt;The following is taken from the book "A History of the Town of Unity, Maine" by James Berry Vickery III, Member of the Maine Histo
2 CONC rical Society and the Essex Institute, published in 1954 by Falmouth Publishing House, Manchester Maine.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</line><line>&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: small;"&gt;*I purchased thi
2 CONC s book at a used book sale April 6, 2019&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</line><line>&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: small;"&gt;Pages 16-18&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</line><line>&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-famil
2 CONC y: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: small;"&gt;One early October day in the year 1783, when the autumn appeared resplendent in colors of crimson and gold, and lofty pines cast long shadows over the dark blue of the lake, a boat containing t
2 CONC wo teenage lads, and a younger lad of eight years, four young girls, the oldest about thirteen, and three adults landed on the southwest shore of the pond, where the Pond Cemetery is located today. This was the family of Stephen and Hannah Chase o
2 CONC f Durham, Maine. Among the group was the seventy year old Mrs. Curtis who was Mrs. Chase's mother. Stephen Chase had previously built the year before (1782) a house of logs overlooking Unity Pond. This was on a part of the "horseback" located a fe
2 CONC w rods beyond the lower end of the Pond cemetery, a spot which in 1948 was completely swept away by the action of a bulldozer gouging out the gravel hillside for the foundations for a modern road.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</line><line>&lt;p&
2 CONC gt;&lt;span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: small;"&gt;Stephen Chase was born in Sawnsea, Massachusetts in the year 1740 and moved to Maine where he was married in 1760 to Hannah Blethen of Georgetown. He next appeare
2 CONC d in Durham, Maine (then Royalsborough) where in 1770 he purchased a farm. At Durham, Chase was a leading citizen for he was elected to serve on a committee to choose a site for a meeting house and cemetery. He remained in Durham about ten years, t
2 CONC hen his restless spirit caused him to move elsewhere, and in the year 1783 made his final settlement in Twenty-Five Mile Pond Plantantion. Hence, he became a pioneer settler of two Maine communities. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</line><line>&lt;p&gt;&lt
2 CONC ;span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: small;"&gt;Full testimony that Chase was a first settler in Unity is provided in the journal of the Reverend Paul Coffin, an itinerant Congregational preacher of Buxton. In 1796 h
2 CONC e made a missionary journey to the settlements east of the Kennebec and early in August of that year visited Stephen Chase. Coffin wrote in his diary, "Stephen Chase is a first and wealthy settler here...a kind of Quaker teacher" Coffin's account o
2 CONC f his visit is not flattering to Chase, but we must not be hasty in accepting the critical comments of this ardent Congregrationalist. Coffin was often quite blunt and prejudiced against any person not of his denomination. He called "Father Chase
2 CONC " a "cidevant Quaker and now an exhorter of no sect." Stephen Chase considered himself as a religious leader in the small settlement. When more settlers came, Chase held meetings and frequently spoke to the people. He was noted for his quaint and w
2 CONC himsical sayings. Coffin's diary shows that Chase preached and baptized much to the consternation of Coffin. &amp;nbsp;Coffin recorded in his diary concerning both Chase and a Baptist preacher, John Whitney, "The deceit of him and Chase at baptizin
2 CONC g was amazing." Coffin accused Chase of deceit; "Chase, the Quaker acted deceitfully in not telling the people of my lectures...The people were angry with Chase for secreting more than publishing my presence and lectures, for some lost the opportun
2 CONC ity of hearing me by his guile." Here is the way Coffin descried his relations with Chase: "&lt;em&gt;Yesterday before lecture, Chase came to me and was almost raptured at my knowledge in the grace of the spirit, and supposing my union with him i
2 CONC n doctrine, called on me before the assembly , to own or reject his notions. I answered with caution and tied his spirit to the word. This answer and my sermon on the quick and powerful word of God cost me his esteem and prevented his glory among t
2 CONC he people which he seemed to hope he should make me the occasion of promoting, by concurring with him. &amp;nbsp;O, how I sank from high esteem to nothing in the space of two hours! O that all new settlements could fully know and feel the damage wh
2 CONC ich these two good men have done in this place."&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</line><line>&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: small;"&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/em&gt;Note that Coffin referred to Cha
2 CONC se and Whitney as "good" men. This points clearly that the chief difference between them was on religious matters, and "Father Chase" was as sincere in his convictions as Coffin. &amp;nbsp;It also seems that Chase had a strong desire to act as "squ
2 CONC ire" of the community and the leader in town affairs; consequently, he had no taste for an outsider like Coffin disturbing community affairs under his jurisdiction.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</line><line>&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: arial, hel
2 CONC vetica, sans-serif; font-size: small;"&gt;The next year Coffin again visited Stephen Chase, but his visit was cut short because Chase desired to engage him in religious argument, which Coffin wished to avoid. "Father Chase talked so much of sacre
2 CONC d writ, and so mixed hetergeneous (sic) matters that I left him after dinner." The observant preacher was impressed with Chase's beautiful upland and intervale farm. "His farm is at the southwest end. The prospect is admirably good. From his seat t
2 CONC o a point one-half mile off on the west side of the house the walk is nearly equal to Boston Common."&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</line></content></metadataxml>
