2 TITL Dames 1639
1 _OID a55d43c6-2f5d-4604-9300-e5c7027d8472
1 _META <metadataxml><content><line>&lt;p style="line-height: 1.38; margin-: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: arial; color: #4e453f; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: no
2 CONC rmal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;"&gt;Jones COUNTY &amp;nbsp;GA Bios Dame Family &amp;nbsp;File contributed for use in USGenWeb Archives by JHern10274@@aol.com Dr. James Herndon &amp;nbsp;http://files.usg
2 CONC warchives.org/ga/jones/bios/dame.txt From History of Jones County, Georgia 1807-1907, by Carolyn White Williams, pp. 604-606. &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;DAME &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</line><line>&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</line>
2 CONC <line>&lt;p style="line-height: 1.38; margin-: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: arial; color: #4e453f; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration
2 CONC : none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;"&gt;The Dame family first in France then in England, originally came from Denmark. &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;The first was with Rollo and invaded France. Sometimes written as Dane or Dam. First &am
2 CONC p;nbsp;to come to America of the line was John Dame to Dover, N.H. in 1639 (corrected from error in text citing 1939). &amp;nbsp;In 1750 Solomon Dame went to West Point, Va. Two generations later John, Richard, George, Charles and mother came to Ge
2 CONC orgia. &amp;nbsp;Geo. and John settled in what is now Jones Co. and built a ferry, since known as Dames Ferry. Relatives, Jarvis, Green and others settled here, built houses on the Ocmulgee river. &amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 1
2 CONC 2pt; font-family: arial; color: #4e453f; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;"&gt;Their house was built as a fort, so all th
2 CONC e families could get together in case the &amp;nbsp;Indians attacked. The boards were three or four inches thick, 14 in. wide, timbers heavy &amp;nbsp;and strong, built on top of the hill. Holes were cut to allow for firing without leaving the &amp
2 CONC ;nbsp;house. The building has been torn down but the heavy timbers were used in other houses later. &amp;nbsp;Negroes live there now, descendant of slaves who came down from Virginia with the Dames. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 12pt; fon
2 CONC t-family: arial; color: #4e453f; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;"&gt;Three cemeteries there are filled with members of th
2 CONC e family. &amp;nbsp;A large stone marks the grave of Mary Dame, mother of the Georgia Dames came from Virginia. &amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: arial; color: #4e453f; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400
2 CONC ; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;"&gt;The ferry was made in 1810, and is still in use. &amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: arial; col
2 CONC or: #4e453f; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;"&gt;Four boys fought in war 1812-1814 with England. &amp;nbsp;Richard and Ch
2 CONC arles enlisted in Georgia. John and George went back, enlisted in Virginia, but came back after the &amp;nbsp;war. Geo. moved to Montgomery Co. then to Clinch Co. where he died. Richard and Chas. Moved to North Georgia. Arrowheads of Indians can b
2 CONC e found on the Dames &amp;nbsp;property there until this day, the Indians' arrow-maker lived there. John Dame mar. two of the dau. of Zachariah Booth, a justice and a prominent man in the County. &amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 12
2 CONC pt; font-family: arial; color: #4e453f; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;"&gt;John A. Harris, a widower of Ebbie Drusilla D
2 CONC ame lived at Gray, chil. Marie and &amp;nbsp;Violet. Aubrey Dame, Macon, Ga. Mrs. Mary Virginia Bergman, dau. of Shelby Taylor &amp;nbsp;Dame, lives in Forsyth, Ga. P.O. Box 182. She first married Henry Wiggins. A son named Wiggins lives in Toccoa
2 CONC , was Rep. in Ga. Leg., now Sec. to Gov. &amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: arial; color: #4e453f; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; verti
2 CONC cal-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;"&gt;William B. Dame mar. Julia C. Gresham, dau. was Elizabeth Dame, mar. Andrew &amp;nbsp;L. Harris, their chil. Lomie Harris, Reba, Homer Hugh, Emmie M., Gussie L., Leon &amp;nbsp;Harris. JOHN DAME LIN
2 CONC E OF ANCESTERS (sic.) &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: arial; color: #4e453f; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-sp
2 CONC ace: pre-wrap;"&gt;Gen. 1. &amp;nbsp;John Dame of Hartfordshire to Dover, N.H. &amp;nbsp;Wife not now known. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: arial; color: #4e453f; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style
2 CONC : normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;"&gt;Gen. 2. &amp;nbsp;John Dame, b. 8th Jan., 1637, at Dover, d. 8th Jan. 1706. &amp;nbsp;Wife: Elizabeth Furber, dau. Lt. Wm. Furber, he wa
2 CONC s a Sergeant in the Indian Wars. &amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: arial; color: #4e453f; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-alig
2 CONC n: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;"&gt;Gen. 3. &amp;nbsp;Moses Dame, b. 16th Oct., 1673, at Dover, d. at Newington, N.H. in 1754. &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Married Abigail Huntress, dau. of Geo. He was one of the founders of Newington &amp;nbsp;Church
2 CONC . &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: arial; color: #4e453f; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;"&gt;G
2 CONC en. 4. &amp;nbsp;Solomon Dame, b. Aug. 1722, d. cir. 1780 at Newington. &amp;nbsp;Married Martha Brooking, dau. of John Brooking. First to come South and settled at Roy's Neck, &amp;nbsp;near West Point, Va. In 1750. Member Straton-Major Episcopa
2 CONC l Church. 5. George Dame, b. 1752, in King and Queen Co., Va. d. in Christ Church Parish &amp;nbsp;near Urbanna, Va., 1805. Married Mary Green, dau. of Nicholas Green and his wife, Elizabeth (dau. of Aijalon Price). His chil. Were Mary Green Dame
2 CONC , b. 1780, mar. John &amp;nbsp;Jarvis. James, b. 1783, d. in infancy. George Dame, b. 8th Mch, 1784, Va. Elizabeth Price Dame, b. in Va., moved to Ga. Ann Dame, b. in Va. (These moved to Georgia with family). &amp;nbsp;John Brooking Dame, 9th Feb.
2 CONC , 1789, at Christ Church Parish, Va. Died 24th Jan., 1845, in Jones County. Gen. 6. John Brooking Dame, b. 9th Feb., 1789 in Christ Church Parish, Va., and &amp;nbsp;died in Jones Co., Ga., 24th Jan. 1845. Married (1) Polly Booth, dau. of Zacharia
2 CONC h Booth. One child, Elizabeth Green Dame, died in infancy. Polly (Mary), b. 7th Jan., 1794, d. 17th Jan., 1814. &amp;nbsp;Married (2) Mildred (Milly) Booth, sister of 1st wife, was born 25th Sept., 1799, d. 4th Oct., 1867. Children 2nd wife: Mary U
2 CONC pshaw Dame 26th Apr., 1816, d. 10th Mch., 1886. Married&amp;hellip;&amp;hellip;&amp;hellip;&amp;hellip;. (an apparent omission). &amp;nbsp;James L. Dame, 17th Dec. 1817, d. 19th Aug. 1819. Henry Green Dame, b. 23rd Sept., 1820, d. 11th Oct., 1875
2 CONC . Married Elizabeth Lloyd in 1847. William Brooking Dame, b. 1st Mar. [1823], d. 14th Jan., 1856. Mar. Abigail Catherine Coulter. &amp;nbsp;Charles L. Dame, b. 25th Feb., 1825, mar. Martha Morris. Martha W. Dame, b. 8th May, 1829, mar. Robert P. Ha
2 CONC rking (Harkins). Sarah Ann, 19th Apr., 1827, d. 25th Sept., 1831. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: arial; color: #4e453f; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decorati
2 CONC on: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;"&gt;Some descendants of this family are: &amp;nbsp;Dr. George A. Dame of Jacksonville, Fla. &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Judge Flem C. Dame of Fort Pierce, Fla. John W. Dame of Winter Haven, Fla. &a
2 CONC mp;nbsp;Mrs. A.J. Gibbs, Mrs. H.M. Peagler, George D. Peagler, Mrs. A.L. Barnhill, Mrs. A.J. Gibbs &amp;nbsp;(repeated), and many others. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: arial; color: #4e453f; background-color: #ffffff; f
2 CONC ont-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;"&gt;Stones at the old cemetery reads (sic.): &amp;nbsp;Mary Green Dame, widow of George Dame of Middlesex Co., Va., b
2 CONC . Culpepper Co., Va. 1753, d. June 29, 1832. &amp;nbsp;C.L. Dame, b. Feb. 25, 1825, d. July 18, 1881. William B. Dame, b. March 2, 1848, d. August 3, 1899. The old ferry is still there, transporting about 100 cars on Sundays and averaging &amp;nbsp
2 CONC ;15 a day for the week. ======================== USGENWEB NOTICE: In keeping with our policy of providing free information on the Internet, data may be freely used by non-commercial entities, as long as this message remains on all copied material
